solution.approach:
We process the array from right to left. For each position i we need Ai ≤ A(i+1). If Ai is already ≤ A(i+1) nothing is done. Otherwise we repeatedly replace Ai by floor(sqrt(Ai)) – the only operation that can decrease a value – counting each replacement as one operation, until Ai ≤ A(i+1). Because sqrt strictly decreases any number > 1, this loop always terminates (the value eventually becomes 1). Squaring would only increase a value and can never help when the current element is too large, therefore the greedy choice of only using sqrt is optimal. The total number of performed sqrt operations is the answer.

Algorithm:
1. Read the array.
2. ans = 0.
3. For i = N‑2 downto 0:
   while A[i] > A[i+1] and A[i] > 1:
       A[i] = floor(sqrt(A[i]));
       ans++;
4. Output ans.

Complexities: Each sqrt reduces the number at least to its square root, so an element of size up to 10^18 needs at most about log2(log2(10^18)) < 7 reductions. Hence the total time is O(N) per test case, and O(N) memory.

code.C:
#include <stdio.h>
#include <math.h>
#include <inttypes.h>

static unsigned long long isqrt_ull(unsigned long long x){
    unsigned long long r = (unsigned long long)sqrt((long double)x);
    while ((r+1)*(r+1) <= x) ++r;
    while (r*r > x) --r;
    return r;
}

int main(){
    int T; if(scanf("%d", &T)!=1) return 0;
    while(T--){
        int N; scanf("%d", &N);
        unsigned long long a[N];
        for(int i=0;i<N;i++) scanf("%" SCNu64, &a[i]);
        unsigned long long ops = 0;
        for(int i=N-2;i>=0;--i){
            while(a[i] > a[i+1] && a[i] > 1){
                a[i] = isqrt_ull(a[i]);
                ++ops;
            }
        }
        printf("%" PRIu64 "\n", ops);
    }
    return 0;
}

